    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="1492"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1492">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/250</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                    <gloss type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 20, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 21, 11.15 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2089. Have received letter from Minister for Foreign Affairs stating he has
                    telegraphed German Legation, The Hague, authorizing it <pb facs="1296" n="1038"
                        xml:id="pg_1038"/> to issue letters of escort to ships of commission, not
                    only for return voyage to America, but also for trip to England provided ships
                    are required by terms of charter to return to England and they take no cargo for
                    England. For safety of ships strongly urged that they carry by day and by night
                    clearly recognizable identification markings. Also recommend that ships of
                    commission returning to America should not call at English ports solely for
                    coaling, but should coal at Rotterdam where German coal will be provided if
                    possible. German submarines already instructed to let ships of commission pass
                    unmolested when recognizable as such.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
